.SH "NAME"
.IX Header "NAME"
guess_media_type \- guess media type for a file or a URL.
.PP
media_suffix \- returns file extentions for a media type
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.PP
.Vb 2
\& use LWP::MediaTypes qw(guess_media_type);
\& $type = guess_media_type("/tmp/foo.gif");
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module provides functions for handling of media (also known as
MIME) types and encodings.  The mapping from file extentions to media
types is defined by the \fImedia.types\fR file.  If the \fI~/.media.types\fR
file exist it is used as a replacement.
.PP
For backwards compatability we will also look for \fI~/.mime.types\fR.
.SH "FUNCTIONS"
.IX Header "FUNCTIONS"
.Sh "\fIguess_media_type\fR\|($filename_or_url, [$header_to_modify])"
.IX Subsection "\fIguess_media_type\fR\|($filename_or_url, [$header_to_modify])"
This function tries to guess media type and encoding for given file.
In scalar context it returns only the content-type.  In array context
it returns an array consisting of content-type followed by any
content-encodings applied.
.PP
The guess_media_type function also accepts a \s-1URI::URL\s0 object as argument.
.PP
If the type can not be deduced from looking at the file name only,
then \fIguess_media_type()\fR will take a look at the actual file using the
\f(CW-T\fR perl operator in order to determine if this is a text file
(text/plain).  If this does not work it will return
\fIapplication/octet-stream\fR as the type.
.PP
The optional second argument should be a reference to a \s-1HTTP::\s0Headers
object (or some \s-1HTTP::\s0Message object).  When present this function
will set the value of the \*(L'Content-Type\*(R' and \*(L'Content-Encoding\*(R' for
this header.
.Sh "\fImedia_suffix\fR\|($type,...)"
.IX Subsection "\fImedia_suffix\fR\|($type,...)"
This function will return all suffixes that can be used to denote the
specified media \fItype\fR\|(s).  Wildcard types can be used.  In scalar
context it will return the first suffix found.
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&  @suffixes = media_suffix('image/*', 'audio/basic');
\&  $suffix = media_suffix('text/html');
.Ve

